<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="51" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
The type species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Walsingham &amp; Durrant, 1909" authorityName="Walsingham &amp; Durrant" authorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Heliozelidae" genus="Holocacista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holocacista" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Holocacista</taxonomicName>
has recently been diagnosed in the context of a study of European (and North American) 
<taxonomicName family="Vitaceae" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" rank="family">Vitaceae</taxonomicName>
miners (
<bibRefCitation author="Nieukerken, EJ van" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="29" pageNumber="70" pagination="29 - 77" title="Antispilaoinophylla new species (Lepidoptera, Heliozelidae), a new North American grapevine leafminer invading Italian vineyards: taxonomy, DNA barcodes and life cycle." url="10.3897/zookeys.170.2617" volume="170" year="2012 b">van Nieukerken et al. 2012b</bibRefCitation>
), when the genus was still considered monotypic. Here we briefly diagnose it against other species in the genus, without a full redescription. It should be noted that only material from Italy and Bulgaria has been examined in detail. Morphological details (Figs 21, 23, 24, 26) and venation (Fig. 29) are described under the generic treatment. For a full synonymy we refer to 
<bibRefCitation author="Nieukerken, EJ van" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="29" pageNumber="70" pagination="29 - 77" title="Antispilaoinophylla new species (Lepidoptera, Heliozelidae), a new North American grapevine leafminer invading Italian vineyards: taxonomy, DNA barcodes and life cycle." url="10.3897/zookeys.170.2617" volume="170" year="2012 b">van Nieukerken et al. (2012b)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="51" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Differential diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
(Fig. 9). Wingspan 4.0-4.5 mm. Antenna ringed, 15 segments; head and thorax bronze grey. Forewing fuscous to black, with golden silvery pattern consisting of four spots, costals distal to dorsals, the first costal and dorsal sometimes united as oblique fascia; a distinct fringe line, fringe silvery white. Differs from South African 
<taxonomicName authority="Walsingham &amp; Durrant, 1909" authorityName="Walsingham &amp; Durrant" authorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Heliozelidae" genus="Holocacista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holocacista capensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capensis">Holocacista capensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Walsingham &amp; Durrant, 1909" authorityName="Walsingham &amp; Durrant" authorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Heliozelidae" genus="Holocacista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holocacista salutans" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salutans">Holocacista salutans</taxonomicName>
by more golden shining spots and distinct first costal spot (almost absent or reduced in other species); from 
<taxonomicName authority="Walsingham &amp; Durrant, 1909" authorityName="Walsingham &amp; Durrant" authorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Heliozelidae" genus="Holocacista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holocacista varii" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varii">Holocacista varii</taxonomicName>
and other species by distinct fringe line and ringed antenna.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
Male genitalia (Fig. 105, and Figs 48-50 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Nieukerken, EJ van" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="29" pageNumber="70" pagination="29 - 77" title="Antispilaoinophylla new species (Lepidoptera, Heliozelidae), a new North American grapevine leafminer invading Italian vineyards: taxonomy, DNA barcodes and life cycle." url="10.3897/zookeys.170.2617" volume="170" year="2012 b">van Nieukerken et al 2012b</bibRefCitation>
). Total length vinculum + tegumen 630-720 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, phallus 575-630 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. Pecten with 8-10 teeth. Juxta more elaborate than in South African 
<taxonomicName family="Vitaceae" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" rank="family">Vitaceae</taxonomicName>
miners, deeply bifurcate. Phallus without spines on phallocrypt, wrinkled. Female genitalia illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Nieukerken, EJ van" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="29" pageNumber="70" pagination="29 - 77" title="Antispilaoinophylla new species (Lepidoptera, Heliozelidae), a new North American grapevine leafminer invading Italian vineyards: taxonomy, DNA barcodes and life cycle." url="10.3897/zookeys.170.2617" volume="170" year="2012 b">van Nieukerken et al (2012b</bibRefCitation>
, Figs 51-52) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Cean, M" journalOrPublisher="from southern Romania Scientific Papers Series A Agronomy" pageId="27" pageNumber="68" pagination="385 - 388" title="Holocacistarivillei (Stainton, 1855) (LepidopteraHeliozidae) - a leafminer species recorded on Vitisvinifera L." url="http://agronomyjournal.usamv.ro/pdf/2014/art69.pdf" volume="57" year="2014">Cean (2014)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="51" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
Host plants. 
<taxonomicName family="Vitaceae" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" rank="family">Vitaceae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Vitaceae" genus="Vitis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Vitis vinifera" order="Vitales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vinifera">Vitis vinifera</taxonomicName>
, wild and cultivated, possibly also on cultivated 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Vitaceae" genus="Parthenocissus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Parthenocissus" order="Vitales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Parthenocissus</taxonomicName>
Planch. (new record from Russia, Kalmykiya).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
Leafmines (Figs 87, 88). The egg is inserted usually close to a major vein, probably on leaf underside. The mine is first a gallery, turning from once to several times around the oviposition site and then extends, often along a vein as a rather straight linear mine, occasionally as a serpentine mine; distally enlarging into a small blotch. The frass is black forming a broken line, often not exactly in the middle of the mine; in thicker leaves it may be wider; in the blotch the frass is dispersed; the larva cuts out a case of about 3.3-4 mm 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.0-2.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="51" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
Widespread in southern Europe, Turkey and Central Asia (
<bibRefCitation author="Nieukerken, EJ van" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="29" pageNumber="70" pagination="29 - 77" title="Antispilaoinophylla new species (Lepidoptera, Heliozelidae), a new North American grapevine leafminer invading Italian vineyards: taxonomy, DNA barcodes and life cycle." url="10.3897/zookeys.170.2617" volume="170" year="2012 b">van Nieukerken et al. 2012b</bibRefCitation>
), now also recorded in Romania (
<bibRefCitation author="Cean, M" journalOrPublisher="from southern Romania Scientific Papers Series A Agronomy" pageId="27" pageNumber="68" pagination="385 - 388" title="Holocacistarivillei (Stainton, 1855) (LepidopteraHeliozidae) - a leafminer species recorded on Vitisvinifera L." url="http://agronomyjournal.usamv.ro/pdf/2014/art69.pdf" volume="57" year="2014">Cean 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Probably only native in eastern part of its current distribution area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
